<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - books-arts]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/books-arts <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/books-arts" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - books-arts - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 18 日星期二 18:08:44 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Silicon Valley Money Men Are Buzzing About Robert F. Kennedy Jr.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Twitter 联合创始人杰克·多尔西 (Jack Dorsey) 等人赞扬总统候选人<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815062/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="小罗伯特·F·肯尼迪正在与拜登总统争夺民主党总统提名。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>小罗伯特·F·肯尼迪正在与拜登总统争夺民主党总统提名。苏菲·帕克 (Sophie Park) 为《华尔街日报》<span>拍摄 苏菲·帕克 (Sophie Park) 为《华尔街日报》拍摄</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001045641"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001045641"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/angel-au-yeung" itemprop="url" rel="author">Angel Au-Yeung</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/berber-jin" itemprop="url" rel="author">Berber Jin</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 17 日晚上 9:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/silicon-valley-money-men-are-buzzing-about-robert-f-kennedy-jr-3b5dea5e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>小罗伯特·F·肯尼迪表示，儿童时期的疫苗与自闭症有关，而且中央情报局杀死了他的叔叔。他曾公开表示想知道接触 Wi-Fi 是否会导致癌症。一些科技界的大明星称赞<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/robert-f-kennedy-election-presidential-campaign-2024-5265d2b8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">他的总统竞选活动</a>。</p><p>硅谷喜欢逆向思维，这就是为什么一些科技名人在 2016 年和 2020 年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/investor-peter-thiel-donald-trump-gets-big-things-right-1477934224?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">支持</a>共和党人<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>。这一次，民主党人肯尼迪成为科技界反建制言论的焦点。</p><p> Twitter联合创始人杰克·多尔西最近表示支持肯尼迪，后者正在与拜登总统争夺民主党<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/robert-kennedy-jr-files-to-run-for-president-as-a-democrat-1149fd33?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">总统提名</a>。肯尼迪受到了其他一些科技巨头的款待，包括<strong>&nbsp;</strong> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/when-spac-man-chamath-palihapitiya-speaks-reddit-and-wall-street-listen-11615006818?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">SPAC 国王</a>查马斯·帕里哈皮蒂亚 (Chamath Palihapitiya) 和大卫·萨克斯 (David Sacks)，后者是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/PYPL" class="company-name">PayPal</a>的创始高管，也是埃隆·马斯克 ( <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">Elon Musk)</a>值得信赖的耳朵。现已关闭的文件共享网站 LimeWire 的创始人马克·戈顿 (Mark Gorton) 成立了一个支持肯尼迪的 PAC。</p><p>他们说他们喜欢他愿意打破现状的态度。</p><p> “先生。肯尼迪的竞选活动是关于未来，而不是过去，”前国会议员、肯尼迪竞选经理丹尼斯·库西尼奇说。 “科技界人士希望总统具有前瞻性，希望扩大美国在科技领域的作用，尊重数据隐私，并且在对待政府的方式上具有深刻的创造力。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815059?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Twitter 联合创始人杰克·多尔西 (Jack Dorsey) 表达了对小罗伯特·F·肯尼迪 (Robert F. Kennedy Jr.) 的支持。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：科尔·伯斯顿/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>民意调查普遍认为肯尼迪是十几岁的人。 LinkedIn联合创始人里德·霍夫曼和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NFLX" class="company-name">Netflix</a>联合创始人里德·黑斯廷斯等硅谷权力掮客都支持拜登，预计拜登将成为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/joe-biden-2024-presidential-re-election-campaign-87ef002b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">提名人</a>。</p><p>尽管如此，围绕肯尼迪的关注加上他家族的受欢迎的名字使民主党的初选进程变得复杂化。</p><p>拜登的一名顾问表示：“随着美国人更多地了解他的极端和不受欢迎的记录，他的支持率将继续动摇。”</p><p>据《纽约邮报》首先发表的言论，肯尼迪上周表示，Covid-19 针对的是黑人和白人，而没有放过德系犹太人或华裔。</p><p>他的言论引起了公众的强烈抗议。肯尼迪在一份声明中表示，他被抹黑为反犹太分子。</p><p>科技行业经常被描绘成一个偏爱进步候选人的群体，但情况并非总是如此。</p><p>斯坦福大学商学院政治经济学教授尼尔·马尔霍特拉表示，政府对疫情的反应，包括封锁，是一个转折点，导致一些科技选民在社会问题上变得更加保守。肯尼迪对 Covid-19 疫苗的安全性表示怀疑，并反对封锁。</p><p>事实上，部分美国企业界对两党的领先者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/wall-street-mobilizes-for-a-presidential-election-reluctantly-49b4b735?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">都不感兴趣</a>——前总统特朗普是共和党提名的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-republican-presidential-rivals-criticism-39d476c5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">领先者</a>——也给了他一个机会。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/30ab478b-b2ff-4466-a46e-bcb8a7800795.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>马尔霍特拉说：“罗伯特·肯尼迪代表了这个替代方案，他既不是拜登，也不是特朗普。” “特朗普还背负着许多人（包括科技创始人）不喜欢的其他包袱。”</p><p>肯尼迪是一名环境律师，他的观点引起了其他民主党人（包括他自己的家人）的愤怒。该社交媒体网站当时表示，他的 Instagram 帐户因“分享有关冠状病毒或疫苗的被揭穿的说法”而于 2021 年被删除。 （他宣布竞选总统后，他的账户就恢复了。）</p><p>对于一些人来说，这使他成为一个更有趣的候选人：来自建制派的人似乎想要推翻它。</p><p>支持拜登的政治策略师库珀·特博 (Cooper Teboe) 表示：“硅谷是建立在‘快速行动、打破常规’的理念之上，而不是‘缓慢地通过一个议院然后再通过下一个议院进行谈判’。”硅谷。但蒂博说，拜登长期的政治经验是他成功的关键。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815194?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">前国会议员丹尼斯·库西尼奇 (Dennis Kucinich) 介绍小罗伯特·F·肯尼迪 (Robert F. Kennedy Jr.) 参加 4 月份在波士顿正式宣布的总统竞选活动。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：斯科特·艾森/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>一些关注肯尼迪的科技精英已经与其他候选人调情。例如，萨克斯是佛罗里达州州长<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/ron-desantis">罗恩·德桑蒂斯</a>竞选共和党提名的捐助者。他和马斯克一起在推特上参加了德桑蒂斯的竞选<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ron-desantis-trump-successor-president-3e9df9d6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">活动启动</a>仪式。与此同时，帕里哈皮蒂亚过去曾表示支持前联合国大使、共和党候选人、南卡罗来纳<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nikki-haley-enters-gop-presidential-race-as-first-major-trump-challenger-4f88d0da?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">州</a>州长尼基·黑利(Nikki Haley)。</p><p>帕里哈皮蒂亚在一封电子邮件中说：“表彰那些提出严肃、苛刻问题的人很重要。” “显然，越多的人听到罗伯特·肯尼迪的消息，他们就越同意我们的观点，即他应该参与未来的辩论。”</p><p>萨克斯和多尔西没有回应置评请求。</p><p>多尔西过去曾支持过非传统的总统候选人。 2019 年，他向科技企业家安德鲁·杨 (Andrew Yang) 和前夏威夷国会女议员图尔西·加巴德 (Tulsi Gabbard) 的竞选活动捐款。他们都竞选民主党总统提名。</p><p> LimeWire 创始人戈顿创建了一个名为“美国价值观 2024”的超级政治行动委员会，他说，该组织最初是一个专注于打击“制药行业腐败”的组织。现在它支持肯尼迪的候选资格。</p><p>戈顿在接受采访时表示：“令我感到厌恶的是，民主党已经成为新保守派的政党和大型制药公司的政党。” “我认为他竞选将民主党从腐败利益手中夺回是高尚的。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815197?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">小罗伯特·F·肯尼迪 (Robert F. Kennedy Jr.) 在波士顿发表演讲之前，向观众展示了一张小罗伯特·F·肯尼迪 (Robert F. Kennedy Jr.) 与叔叔泰德·肯尼迪 (Ted Kennedy) 和姑妈尤尼斯·肯尼迪·施赖弗 (Eunice Kennedy Shriver) 的照片。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：布莱恩·斯奈德/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>1980 年，马萨诸塞州参议员泰德·肯尼迪（小罗伯特·F·肯尼迪的叔叔）与吉米·卡特争夺民主党提名，但未能成功。卡特后来在大选中输给了罗纳德·里根。一些人指责特德·肯尼迪<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/if-economy-sours-democrats-will-face-a-tough-choice-11566219836?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">分裂选票</a>。</p><p>曾参与卡特总统竞选活动的民主党政治策略师加里·索斯 (Garry South) 表示，他认为小罗伯特·F·肯尼迪的竞选活动“根本不会上升到那个水平”。</p><p> “泰迪是主流自由民主党人，”南说。 “RFK 就是个疯子。”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您对小罗伯特·F·肯尼迪的竞选有何看法？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>上个月，帕里哈皮蒂亚和萨克斯与另一个支持肯尼迪的组织 Common Sense 联合举办了一场筹款活动。鸡尾酒会的门票为 2,000 美元，晚宴的门票为 10,000 美元。</p><p> Common Sense 女演员兼财务主管索菲亚·卡斯滕斯 (Sofia Karstens) 表示，此次活动在萨克斯位于旧金山的豪宅举行，共有 75 名嘉宾参加，其中大多数来自科技和加密行业。</p><p> 69 岁的肯尼迪比 80 岁的拜登年轻约十岁。上个月，他<a href="https://twitter.com/RobertKennedyJr/status/1673053159172833280" target="_blank" class="icon none">在推特上发布了一段自己赤裸上身在室外健身房做俯卧撑的视频</a>。 “为与拜登总统的辩论做好准备！”他写了。 （民主党全国委员会此前曾表示将支持拜登，不会赞助任何辩论。） </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><amp-twitter width="486" height="657" layout="responsive" data-tweetid="1673053159172833280" data-cards="hidden"></amp-twitter></div><p>加拿大科技高管 Samson Mow 表示，肯尼迪已经表现出一种理解，即比特币等去中心化数字货币可以促进摆脱政府限制的自由。肯尼迪 5 月在迈阿密举行的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/at-bitcoin-conference-no-bears-allowed-46295ad1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">比特币 2023 会议</a>上发表讲话，称加密货币是“对抗政府和企业扩张的堡垒”。</p><p>克林顿政府时期的前华盛顿民主党特工、现供职于加密货币投资公司 Haun Ventures 的克里斯·勒哈恩 (Chris Lehane) 表示，肯尼迪决定参与 Twitter Spaces 和科技界流行的播客等科技平台，这也让他受到了一些科技领袖的喜爱。</p><p> 5月初，肯尼迪出现在由萨克斯和帕里哈皮蒂亚等四位硅谷富豪主持的播客上，不间断地发表了近两个小时的讲话。</p><p> “我一直是反体制的，”帕里哈皮蒂亚说<strong>&nbsp;</strong>播客快结束时。 “拆除所有这些权力机构的想法让我感到高兴。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——伊丽莎·柯林斯对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Angel Au-Yeung <a href="mailto:angel.au-yeung@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">(angel.au-yeung@wsj.com)</a>和 Berber Jin ( <a href="mailto:berber.jin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">berber.jin@wsj.com)</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/silicon-valley-money-men-are-buzzing-about-robert-f-kennedy-jr-3b5dea5e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/silicon-valley-money-men-are-buzzing-about-robert-f-kennedy-jr-3b5dea5e<author><![CDATA[Angel Au-YeungBerber Jin]]></author><category>华尔街日报财经</category><category>WSJ财经-WS</category><category> WSJ公司</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台/工具</category><category>技术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>健康</category><category>免疫接种</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>医疗/程序</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>小罗伯特·F·肯尼迪</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>健康</category><category>免疫接种</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>医疗</category><category>程序</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台</category><category>工具</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[People Have Begun to Love Apple’s Most Hated Product]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>蒂姆·库克曾为苹果地图道歉；现在它是一些人的首选导航应用程序<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-812767/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>照片插图：Rachel Mendelson/《华尔街日报》，Apple<span>照片插图：Rachel Mendelson/《华尔街日报》，Apple</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001035418"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001035418"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ann-marie-alcantara"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-629922/AM" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ann-marie-alcantara" itemprop="url" rel="author">安-玛丽·阿尔坎塔拉</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 17 日晚上 9:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/apple-maps-app-popularity-iphone-8e52aec1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>当你开车去参加聚会时迷路了，有人可能会问：“为什么，你使用了 Apple 地图？”</p><p> 2012 年推出后，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="">苹果</a><span class="company-name-type">的</span>道路地图应用程序很快就陷入了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390443890304578008712527187512?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">混乱的境地</a>。大开曼岛缺乏道路。纽约的曼哈顿大桥看起来就像过山车。澳大利亚官员警告称，其一些导航缺陷<a href="https://www.wsj.com/amp/articles/BL-DGB-25669?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">“可能危及生命”。</a></p><p>苹果首席执行官蒂姆·库克罕<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/BL-DGB-25004?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">见地向客户道歉</a>，并<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204840504578089102411834238?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">解雇了软件主管</a>。该公司随后花了数年时间试图修复该服务。</p><p>现在，根据客户和用户体验分析师的说法，它已经做到了。一些用户正在寻找改用苹果地图的理由，包括其清晰的公共交通方向和具有视觉吸引力的设计。</p><p>虽然苹果可能不需要这款应用来销售更多 iPhone，但该公司在汽车和增强现实耳机方面的远大抱负取决于人们真正喜欢使用的地图。</p><p> “地图已经取得了长足的进步，人们已经注意到了，”苹果软件主管克雷格·费德里吉 (Craig Federighi) 在该公司 2020 年全球开发者大会上表示。</p><p> Jason Rabinowitz 在推出 Apple 地图后非常愤怒，他转而使用 Android，以便更轻松地使用 Google 地图。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/0444f552-0420-430f-8244-1c2ecf5c0eb8.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>但这并没有持续多久。这位 37 岁的航空业分析师于 2015 年重新使用 iPhone。作为纽约人，他更依赖交通路线而不是驾车路线。几年前，在苹果推出一些新的交通功能后，他尝试了苹果地图，结果让他感到惊讶。</p><p>他现在认为苹果地图比谷歌能更好地提供创意、更快的路线，并更好地管理地铁停运的不可预测性。他向来访的朋友和家人推荐这里。</p><p>拉比诺维茨还喜欢苹果地图更清晰的交通视图，而不是谷歌地图更混乱的设计。</p><p>他称谷歌的传输层“丑陋得令人发指”。但他仍然使用谷歌地图开车。</p><h3>追赶</h3><p>据 Canalys 称，虽然所有 iPhone 上都预装了苹果地图，但美国绝大多数 iPhone 都下载了谷歌地图作为替代方案。为了让人们打开苹果地图，苹果必须采用谷歌地图中已经流行的功能，例如街景功能。苹果在 6 月份的开发者大会上表示，用户将能够离线使用地图，这是谷歌多年来提供的另一项功能。</p><p>但一些视觉效果，例如城市的 3D 天桥视图，首先出现在 Apple 地图中。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/atmospheric/amp.html?guid=02B352E6-1FF8-46D5-83C5-FC0FB3A6AC87" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Apple 地图上的增强现实步行路线利用现实世界来引导人们到达目的地。安-玛丽·阿尔坎塔拉/华尔街日报<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>谷歌地图也不断发展，具有诸如沉浸式 3D 视图等功能，可让您<a href="https://blog.google/products/maps/google-maps-updates-io-2023/" target="_blank" class="icon none">查看一天中不同时间的地点</a>，以及用于查找附近商店、餐馆和其他兴趣点的<a href="https://blog.google/products/maps/new-maps-updates-to-help-you-make-the-most-of-the-holidays/" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">AR 工具</a>。</p><p>苹果地图相对于谷歌的最大竞争优势在于其与 iPhone 的更深入集成。任何需要导航的 iOS 服务（从在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/YELP" class="company-name">Yelp</a>中查找餐馆到在“查找”中查找 AirTags）都使用 Apple 地图。用户无法改变这一点。</p><p>用户体验顾问彼得·拉姆齐（Peter Ramsey）曾撰写过有关苹果地图和谷歌地图之间<a href="https://builtformars.com/case-studies/maps" target="_blank" class="icon none">设计差异的</a>文章，他说：“人们本质上很懒，并且会围绕默认选项养成习惯。” “很长一段时间以来，苹果地图的表现非常糟糕，以至于人们主动转向谷歌地图，但随着苹果地图体验的改善，人们采取打破默认行为的动力越来越少。”</p><h3>风格要点</h3><p>简·纳托利,</p>平时是 Google 地图的高级用户，自从 iPhone 提示她在明尼阿波利斯-圣路易斯使用 Apple 地图后，她发现自己在日常生活中更多地使用了 Apple 地图。保罗国际机场。该应用程序知道她在机场，并为她的航站楼内的商店和餐馆提供建议。这位 42 岁的旧金山政治组织者表示，它比谷歌地图拥有更清晰的信息，更容易互动。 <p></p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="410" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816855?width=700&amp;height=410" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Apple 地图显示机场航站楼内的餐厅和商店。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “这让我重新审视并重新思考我之前对此的一些假设，”纳托利说。 “无论苹果地图最初面临什么声誉障碍，我认为他们已经克服了这些障碍。”</p><p>在机场外，纳托利喜欢苹果的设计，并发现方向更容易阅读，尤其是街道名称。她说，在谷歌地图上，有时无论放大多大，都很难弄清楚街道名称。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您更喜欢苹果地图还是谷歌地图？为什么？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> “谷歌向我展示了餐馆、酒吧和其他东西，但我不一定要寻找这些，”她说。</p><p>最近从佐治亚理工学院毕业的 22 岁女孩 Angelica Nguyen 也有类似的看法。晚上开车时，她发现苹果地图上的道路更容易看清，而且干扰她视野的兴趣点也更少。</p><p> “苹果真的很擅长让东西看起来更漂亮，”Nguyen 说。</p><h3>远非完美</h3><p>在可预见的未来，一些 iPhone 用户仍然会抱怨苹果地图，尤其是当他们觉得地图是强加给他们的时候。</p><p> 23 岁的服装设计专业学生劳拉·普拉兹维奇 (Laura Pladziewicz) 表示，当她在波士顿散步时，她被苹果地图引入了歧途。她在大都会区长大，但不太了解这座城市本身。她遵从苹果地图，因为它是默认地图，而且她承认她没有足够的动力去下载谷歌地图应用程序。</p><p> “尽管它一直让我受委屈，但我已经习惯了伸手去拿它，”她谈到苹果地图时说道。有时，她确实会在手机网络浏览器中的 Google 地图上查找内容。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="418" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815852?width=700&amp;height=418" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">诺亚·阿卜杜勒阿齐兹 (Noah Abdelaziz) 认为，在 CarPlay 上使用 Apple 地图会导致通勤时间延长。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：诺亚·阿卜杜拉齐兹</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>25 岁的法学院学生诺亚·阿卜杜勒阿齐兹 (Noah Abdelaziz) 今年夏天在洛杉矶租了一辆车往返实习。它拥有Apple的车载平台CarPlay，可让驾驶员通过汽车显示屏使用iPhone应用程序和服务。当 Abdelaziz 连接他的 iPhone 时，它​​会自动在主屏幕上显示 Apple 地图。</p><p>他说，为了避免交通堵塞，苹果地图会带他穿过带有停车标志的住宅区，他认为这会增加他的通勤时间。</p><p>他的实习很快结束了。在使用 CarPlay 近一个半月后，他已经学会了如何在 CarPlay 上使用 Google 地图。</p><p> <em>—欲了解更多《华尔街日报》科技分析、评论、建议和头条新闻，</em> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?sub=55&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none"><em>请订阅我们的每周通讯</em></a><em>。</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/824b30d1-428f-4e1d-8a3e-62546516565e.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>写信给 Ann-Marie Alcántara，邮箱为<a href="mailto:ann-marie.alcantara@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ann-marie.alcantara@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/apple-maps-app-popularity-iphone-8e52aec1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/apple-maps-app-popularity-iphone-8e52aec1<author><![CDATA[Ann-Marie Alcántara]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>计算机/消费电子产品</category><category>联网</category><category>汽车电子</category><category>电信设备</category><category>个人电子产品</category><category>机动车零件</category><category>互联网搜索引擎</category><category>汽车</category><category>汽车远程信息处理</category><category>手机/移动电话</category><category>联网汽车技术</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>电子导航/跟踪系统</category><category>卫星导航系统</category><category>移动设备</category><category>工业电子</category><category>工业品</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>物联网技术</category><category>技术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>地理/地质学</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>个人技术</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>苹果</category><category>AAPL</category><category>蒂姆·库克</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>地理</category><category>地质学</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>个人技术</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>电脑</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>联网</category><category>汽车电子</category><category>电信设备</category><category>个人电子产品</category><category>机动车辆零件</category><category>互联网搜索引擎</category><category>汽车</category><category>汽车远程信息处理</category><category>细胞</category><category>手机</category><category>互联车辆技术</category><category>电子导航</category><category>追踪系统</category><category>卫星导航系统</category><category>移动设备</category><category>工业电子</category><category>工业品</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>物联网技术</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Theoderic the Great’ Review: The Warrior King]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>狄奥多里克的权力源于他在战斗中的成功。他徒手杀死了一位国王，并用剑将另一位对手切成两半。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590085802732813236"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818743?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">狄奥多里克大帝，东哥特人国王。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：德阿戈斯蒂尼来自盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590085802732813236"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">凯尔·哈珀</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 17 日下午 6:10 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/theoderic-the-great-review-the-warrior-king-d2763acc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>如果有一个罗马版的《1066 and All That》（这部讽刺英国历史的作品），那么 476 年肯定会成为我们集体历史想象中那些可疑的大胆线条之一。就在那时，罗马最后一位皇帝罗穆卢斯·奥古斯都鲁在西方被废黜。在他十个月的统治期间，一方面是古代。另一方面，中世纪。</p><p>那么，从 493 年统治意大利直至 526 年去世的东哥特国王狄奥多里克大帝又将何去何从呢？在这位讲哥特语的武士的统治下，斗兽场仍然充斥着观众的喧嚣，清脆的山水仍然流过渡槽，卡西奥多罗斯和波爱提乌斯等拉丁文学巨擘仍然在元老院任职。</p><p>汉斯·乌尔里希·维默的《狄奥多里克大帝：哥特人之王，罗马人的统治者》是对这位杰出领袖的生活和时代的不朽探索。这是自威廉·恩斯林 (Wilhelm Ensslin) 1947 年传记以来对其主题最重要的论述，而且由于维默先生的书（此处为约翰·诺埃尔·狄龙 (John Noël Dillon) 流畅的英文译本）在广度和复杂性方面超越了前作，因此作者可以荣获最佳著作奖。我们有狄奥多里克的简介。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/a1de8862-2513-4f6a-a639-1ba2a75ef33f.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>狄奥多里克的故事是史诗般的，也是不可思议的。他于 453 年或 454 年出生在争议不断的多瑙河边境地区（可能位于现在的奥地利东部），父亲是一位精锐的哥特战士，母亲的背景却默默无闻。阿提拉最近去世后，狄奥多里克所属的哥特部落刚刚摆脱匈奴人的长期统治。 461 年，男孩狄奥多里克被运送到君士坦丁堡作为条约的保险。他在罗马帝国的大都市度过了近十年的青少年时期。</p><p>维默强调，狄奥多里克的权力与其说是源自他显赫的血统，也不是源自哥特式对王室合法性的尊重，而是源自他作为一名战士的成功。作为一个暴发户王子，他亲手杀死了萨尔马提亚国王巴拜。作为一支可怕的哥特军队的指挥官，他被证明是东罗马帝国善变的盟友，而东罗马帝国的皇帝本身并不是忠诚的典范。 480年代初期，他被罗马人任命为总司令。几年之内，他就围攻君士坦丁堡。</p><p>如果他的职业生涯就此结束，狄奥多里克的名字将属于动荡不安的五世纪杰出的雇佣军军阀之一。但命运眷顾勇敢者，狄奥多里克还有更远大的抱负。 488 年，他与大约 100,000 名追随者（男人、女人和儿童）一起乘坐武装车队出发，从多瑙河沿岸（位于现在的保加利亚）前往意大利，踏上一段充满不确定性的旅程。他们的目标是推翻罗穆卢斯·奥古斯特鲁斯的废黜者奥多亚塞，并为自己找到一个永久的家。狄奥多里克将奥多亚塞和他的军队逼入了拉文纳的主要据点，两人签署了一份旨在分享权力的条约。该条约持续了大约 10 天，之后狄奥多里克亲手将他的对手劈成两半（维默先生告诉我们，“用一剑，将他从锁骨到臀部切开”）。从这样的血腥开始，意大利出现了一代和平。</p><p>维默先生的调查之所以如此丰富，是因为他对古代黄昏研究的掌握。狄奥多里克的统治几乎切入了这一时期学者之间每一次重大辩论的核心。他笔下的东哥特人本质上是日耳曼部落，还是种族身份是一个被偶然的权力动态重新配置的虚构？</p><p>对于埃尔兰根-纽伦堡大学古代史教授维默来说，东哥特人是一个“暴力社会”，其物质基础是战争和掠夺。但作者认识到，追随狄奥多里克踏上意大利冒险之旅的群众是一群拥有共同历史和文化的民族，这使他们与意大利当地人区别开来，并拉近了他们与其他群体的距离，例如定居在西班牙和高卢的西哥特人。 。</p><p>维默先生对狄奥多里克国内外政策的主线的阐述令人信服。在国内，狄奥多里克追求哥特人和罗马人之间的功能专业化。前者是战士（如果也是地主），后者是平民。双轨政府反映了这种基本的分工。狄奥多里克寻求互补，而不是融合。</p><p>在国外，他寻求东罗马首都的合法性以及后罗马西部的稳定。通过战略条约和汪达尔人、西哥特人、法兰克人、勃艮第人和其他人之间惊人的联姻联盟网络，狄奥多里克成为君士坦丁堡以西最强大的统治者。由于机会主义的扩张，他控制了巴尔干半岛的大片地区、高卢南部的大部分地区和（名义上的）伊比利亚半岛。在六世纪初，法兰克王国是否会变得更加持久和重要并不明显。</p><p>如果说这本书有一个弱点的话，那就是试图解释狄奥多里克的成就如何如此迅速而彻底地解开的谜团。维默先生很好地描述了动荡的最后几年，包括在狄奥多里克的命令下处决波伊提乌斯的永恒污点。但关于狄奥多里克统治的后果却太少了。一场继承危机，然后被查士丁尼重新征服，接着是黑死病的毁灭性到来（维默先生低估了这一点），使东哥特人的实验结束了不光彩的结局。众所周知，在意大利的考古记录中，哥特式存在的物质痕迹很少。哥特人的彻底消亡和相对隐匿与一代人之后到来的伦巴第人形成鲜明对比。他们用武力从罗马人手中夺取了意大利半岛的大部分地区，并统治了两个世纪——没有一个像狄奥多里克一半伟大的领导人。</p><p>通过某种阴暗的过程，狄奥多里克的记忆在伯尔尼的迪特里希的传说中被保留或扭曲。再后来，他的遗产成为现代德国身份观念的密码。但在维默先生冷静的传记中，我们有机会看到一个不容易符合古代或中世纪简单概念的人和时刻。</p><p><em>哈珀先生是俄克拉荷马大学教授，也是圣达菲研究所分形学院的成员。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 22:10:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/theoderic-the-great-review-the-warrior-king-d2763acc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/theoderic-the-great-review-the-warrior-king-d2763acc<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Ballad of Darren’ by Blur Review: Reflective British Rock]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Blur 仍然由 Gorillaz 联合创作人 Damon Albarn 领导，在中断期后回归，比以往任何时候都更加自信，推出了第九张录音室专辑，该专辑有利于歌曲创作的坚实基础。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590093961998203380"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818269?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">模糊</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：鲁本·巴斯蒂安·刘易斯</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590093961998203380"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">马克·理查森</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 17 日下午 5:15 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-ballad-of-darren-by-blur-review-reflective-british-rock-547ae7f3"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Blur 已经经历了很长一段时间，似乎或多或少已经解体，四位成员——主唱兼吉他手达蒙·阿尔本 (Damon Albarn)、主音吉他手格雷厄姆·考克森 (Graham Coxon)、贝斯手亚历克斯·詹姆斯 (Alex James) 和鼓手戴夫·朗特里 (Dave Rowntree)——之间的关系是出了名的紧张。在 1994 年的“Parklife”和 1999 年的“13”等发行的专辑中，这种紧张感在经典专辑中得到了体现，这些专辑从讽刺和真诚的角度来探讨英国生活。在贯穿 2003 年“Think Tank”的这一系列顶级素材中，乐队不断进行实验，从精益的低保真摇滚转向管弦乐盛况，再到带有电子色彩的美妙音乐。尽管 Blur 在 90 年代中期处于鼎盛时期是英伦流行音乐的基石，但与当时的大多数同行不同的是，它一直在不断前进，直到乐队决定暂时转向其他领域。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818266?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption></figure></div><p>在过去的 20 年里，Blur 从 Albarn 先生的主要出路变成了他只有在心情好时才会重访的地方，而那些时光在英国受到了欢乐的庆祝。就在一个多星期前，乐队在伦敦的两晚门票都售空了。伦敦温布利体育场拥有 90,000 个座位。但在美国，这支重要且富有冒险精神的摇滚乐队从未在商业上取得突破。 Blur 2015 年排行榜最高的专辑《The Magic Whip》排名第 24 位，恰好与 Gorillaz 的八张录音室 LP 中排行榜最低的专辑排名相同，Albarn 先生与视觉艺术家 Jamie Hewlett 共同负责该项目。后者的几张唱片已跻身前 5 名。 Blur 的第九张专辑《The Ballad of Darren》（Parlophone/华纳）于周五发行，距 Gorillaz 最新唱片《Cracker Island》发行仅五个月。一个有趣的比较点。</p><p>这是 Blur 最简单、最直接的完整版本——它在强调基础知识的同时，对声音的华丽程度也很轻。如果风险意识不足，Blur 可以用一流的歌曲创作和令人印象深刻的经济来弥补。开场曲“The Ballad”有一段可爱的钢琴旋律和适合其标题的节奏，而这首歌本身在一定程度上是关于变老和调整一个人的期望。阿尔本先生唱出了当“歌谣为你而来”时所发生的事情，他使用更安静、更具反思性的形式来比喻死亡，但只是眨了眨眼睛。</p><p>这是一种有趣而苦乐参半的情绪——下面的曲目“St.查尔斯广场，”完全颠倒了。这是专辑中唯一一首不折不扣的摇滚乐——以乐队的标准来看是相当柔和的一首——而且它具有吸引人的冲击力，还有考克森先生优美的锯齿状吉他副歌。 “每一代人都有其镀金的装腔作势者，”阿尔本先生唱道，如果他在 1995 年发表这句话，那么他的歌词会产生截然不同的效果。那时，这可能是对一个嫉妒的仇恨者的讽刺。现在，它看起来既有趣又懂事，因为艺术家早已不再需要关心别人的想法了。</p><p> 《达伦之歌》中的许多歌词既异想天开，又令人厌倦，暗示着友谊和浪漫似乎已经崩溃，但却是在孤立的地方发生的。其他人则在政治崩溃和关系破裂的场景之间切换，但阿尔本先生以诗意和智慧的眼光表达了如此沉重的情感。 “你现在在哪里？”他在庄严的“俄罗斯弦乐”开头问道，后来唱道：“公寓楼轰然倒塌/戴上耳机你就听不到那么多。”在第六首歌《自恋者》中，阿尔本先生首先说他看着镜子，看到“很多人站在那里”，他似乎在回顾自己的失败，并为下次做得更好而打气。 。他在和弦进行和和声结构上呈现出断裂而令人愉快的有趣线条，接近完美——每一个微妙的音乐转折都既令人舒适又熟悉，又令人惊讶地新颖。</p><p>考克森先生的吉他作品自始至终都是引人注目且高效的。在《再见阿尔伯特》中，他在一条随着展开而破裂的扭曲引导线和令人想起罗伯特·弗里普的梦幻氛围的气体嗡嗡声之间滑动。结尾的“高地”有一个最后的部分，它不断构建，直到它似乎要在噪音的火球中爆炸；然后声音突然中断，专辑就这样结束了。 《The Ballad of Darren》是一张简短的唱片——10首曲目，36分钟——而且在很多地方听起来都与《Cracker Island》非常相似。这两个版本都避免了极端，淡化了过去的实验，并首先展示了精心制作的歌曲的力量。虽然很难不错过 Blur 在千禧年巅峰时期令人眼花缭乱的傲慢，但乐队致力于将其发展到今天的程度，这本身就是自信的标志。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。理查森是《华尔街日报》的摇滚和流行音乐评论家。在 Twitter 上关注他@MarkRichardson。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 21:15:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-ballad-of-darren-by-blur-review-reflective-british-rock-547ae7f3</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-ballad-of-darren-by-blur-review-reflective-british-rock-547ae7f3<category>艺术评论</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Divorce Parties Are a New Hot Invite. ‘It Sort of Ended Up as a Really Fun Funeral.’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>随着社会广泛接受破裂的婚姻，许多刚刚离婚的人更有勇气对自己进行抨击。 &#39;错误结束&#39; <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-814552?width=1000&amp;height=562" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>视频：瓦夏·科洛图沙<span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001042895"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001042895"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/lane-florsheim" itemprop="url" rel="author">莱恩·弗洛舍姆</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 17 日上午 7:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/divorce-parties-registries-marriage-1ed745b9"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web
          bigtophero
"></div><p>布兰迪·斯特勒斯 (Brandi Stellers) 离婚后，她邀请密友参加五月的一场晚会。她调制了招牌鸡尾酒，挂上了“再见费利西亚”的横幅，并分发假玫瑰花瓣并抛向空中。</p><p>派对装饰品包括一张从中间撕下来的一对企鹅的照片。</p><p> “我把企鹅撕成两半，因为企鹅是一夫一妻制的鸟类，应该终身交配，”她说。 “好吧，我不再是你的企鹅了。”</p><p>新近离婚的人正在为自己举办井喷式的狂欢，以纪念他们从不幸的婚姻中解放出来，就像反向单身派对一样。在俄亥俄州哥伦布市一家云计算公司工作的斯特勒斯说：“我想庆祝的不是离婚，而是一个新的篇章，与那些我爱的人一起庆祝，他们都希望我过得最好。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="803" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817952?width=639&amp;height=803" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">布兰迪·斯特勒斯在她的离婚后晚会上。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：布兰迪·斯特勒斯</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>在历史的大部分时间里，离婚并不是一件被全世界吹捧的事件。现在，文化转变正在进行。美国的离婚率一直在下降，但那些离婚的人却可以更自由地宣扬自己的分手。盖洛普民意调查显示，认为离婚在道德上可以接受的美国成年人数量已创历史新高。</p><p> “由于社会压力和刻板印象，离婚曾经是一件令人羞耻的事情，”离婚律师妮可·索多玛（Nicole Sodoma）说，她就这个话题写了《请不要说对不起》一书。 “但今天，人们真的决定消除这种社会耻辱，转而接受离婚作为我们中的一些人经历的人生的另一个阶段。”</p><p>在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ETSY" class="company-name">Etsy</a>和亚马逊上，品牌出售 splitsville 的周边商品，包括“End of an Error”腰带、“Thank U Next”玫瑰金箔气球和“I do.我做到了。我完成了”T 恤。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/PINS" class="">Pinterest</a>数据洞察全球总监 Swasti Sarna 表示<span class="company-name-type">，</span>在分享创意的在线平台 Pinterest 上，“搜索趋势表明人们正在以新的视角看待离婚”。</p><p> 2022 年 6 月，Pinterest 上“离婚派对游戏”的搜索量同比增长 80%，“离婚蛋糕”的搜索量同比增长 50%。 Pinterest 的数据显示，离婚派对装饰创意（35%）和“离婚礼物”（30%）的搜索量也出现了激增。</p><p> “这只是一种感觉，我并不为此感到羞耻，”曼哈顿和布鲁克林的房地产经纪人纳丁·亚当森 (Nadine Adamson) 说，她举办了一场离婚派对。 “我认为在纽约结婚超过 10 年——我结婚 12 年——是一个巨大的成功。”</p><p>亚当森让朋友从洛杉矶飞往纽约，他们预订了她结婚时住过的酒店套房。 “在同一家酒店欣赏同样的景色，感觉就像以一种非常美妙的方式结束了，”她说。</p><p>他们四人在套房里烧鼠尾草，以消除负面情绪，在房间里放满气球，出去吃饭，然后过夜。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="696" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817050?width=700&amp;height=696" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">纳丁·亚当森 (Nadine Adamson) 在她的离婚派对上，在她参加婚礼的酒店房间里。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：克里斯塔·蕾妮</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>亚当森还继续在 Instagram 上发布话题标签#divorceparty，并不是因为她一直扔它们，而是为了突出她的新生活，比如用舒适的燃木壁炉升级她的上流社会。</p><p> “我猜离婚派对是一回事？”几个月前，一位 Reddit 用户发表了一篇帖子，吸引了近 4,000 条评论。海报上有一张来自一对正在举办联合派对的离婚夫妇的邀请函的照片。 “另外也欢迎——我们的也会在那里！”它说。</p><p>加拿大艾伯塔省的心理健康辅导员克里斯·马克斯 (Kris Marks) 表示，当一位朋友邀请他庆祝离婚时，他最初感到很矛盾。马克斯也是前夫的朋友，他认为他不知道这个派对。</p><p> “我有很多想法，比如，我们应该庆祝承诺的结束吗？”马克斯说。 “我反复思考，得出的结论是，是的，婚姻制度就是这样，但如果你选择摆脱它，那是一件很难的事情，应该庆祝一个新的开始。我完全赞成它。”</p><p>他的结婚 12 年的朋友举办了一顿聚餐，然后一行人出去镇上过夜。 “这是我和另一个男人，也许还有 10 个女人，就像是单身派对上墙上的一只苍蝇，”他说。马克斯给他的朋友买了一个月的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dating-apps-paid-memberships-tinder-raya-hinge-11664984612?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Bumble Premium</a>作为礼物。</p><p>一些企业迎合新近离婚的男性。例如，Stripe Street Studio 是一家成立于 2020 年的设计公司，专门帮助离婚和单身男性建立住房。该公司表示，在 Pinterest 上，现在流行的流行语“离婚爸爸审美”的搜索量 6 月份比去年同期增长了近 300%。</p><p>不过，有传闻称，举行彻底离婚游行的女性多于男性。</p><p> “作为一个男人，我们不称之为离婚派对，我们称之为‘我们去喝酒吧，’马克斯解释道。 “我们只是以不同的方式应对。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817046?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">妮可·索多玛 (Nicole Sodoma) 离婚后，买了一辆老式汽车，以 1998 年浪漫喜剧《斯特拉如何找回她的魅力》的名字命名为斯特拉 (Stella)。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Darius Evans/DME Imagery</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>现在，人们可以找到帮助离婚者补充物资的登记网站，因为只有一半的夫妇得到了意大利面机、香料架或 Le Creuset 炊具。</p><p>奥利维亚·德莱森·豪厄尔 (Olivia Dreizen Howell) 于 2019 年分居后，一直住在婚姻住所，但婚姻住所突然变得空荡荡的。 “我的一半东西都不见了，”她说，其他物品都是她婚礼登记处的充满情感的物品。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817051?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">奥利维亚·德莱森·豪厄尔签署离婚文件。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Fresh Starts 登记处</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>因此，她和姐姐 Jenny Dreizen 在 2021 年为有同样经历的人们创立了 Fresh Starts 网站。</p><p>该公司帮助新婚夫妇建立礼物登记处，为新家的特定房间补充库存。最受欢迎的登记项目是厨房和浴室。他们还提供专家网络，例如房地产经纪人、宽恕教练和帮助策划离婚派对的离婚导乐。</p><p> 《艾米丽·波斯特礼仪：百年纪念版》一书的合著者莉齐·波斯特表示，艾米丽·波斯特研究所目前并不认为离婚当事人或离婚后登记是合适的。</p><p>她说：“离婚后与朋友们聚在一起，找到一种方法来结束这一章，感觉良好，这是一件非常令人支持的事情。” “我认为称其为离婚派对感觉有点不切实际。”</p><p>纽约的法律助理艾莉森·麦克怀特 (Allison McWhite) 表示，筹划自己的离婚派对给她带来了一种掌控感。 “很长一段时间以来，似乎有什么事情发生在我身上，向我冲来，而不是我去处理它，”她说。</p><p>她在朋友的公寓里举行了庆祝活动，音乐录影带被投影到墙上，黑色气球散落在地板上，烛台上的蜡滴在装有烛台的空酒瓶上。一个白色蛋糕上涂着樱桃红色的糖霜，上面写着“刚刚离婚”。麦克怀特 (McWhite) 身穿黑色蕾丝透明连衣裙，涂着红色口红，身穿毛皮大衣，符合<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/forget-wedding-dresses-divorce-style-has-arrived-11612616414?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">20 世纪 50 年代离婚时尚</a>派对着装要求。 （想想玛丽莲·梦露 1954 年与乔·迪马吉奥离婚时的情景，当时她穿着小黑裙、脚踩高跟鞋、戴着白手套去法院。） </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/9c101278-b1d5-4ed6-915b-14735a357de8.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>客人们跳舞到凌晨，庆祝她新生活的开始。</p><p> “这最终成为一场非常有趣的葬礼，”麦克怀特说。</p><p>对于一些离婚者来说，试图庆祝可能会适得其反，让人感觉像是在提醒他们失去亲人。</p><p> “当你离婚时，你就失去了一半的朋友，”伦敦的离婚律师阿伊莎·瓦尔达格 (Ayesha Vardag) 说，她的朋友鼓励她在离婚后举办派对。在他们的坚持下，她在一家酒吧楼上预订了一间不错的房间，她说那里有吵闹的音乐和“一些舞蹈，但还不够，因为人确实不够多。”</p><p> “为了好玩，压力很大，”她说。 “后来，我觉得我应该让自己感到非常沮丧，然后慢慢走出困境。”</p><p>旅游博主玛雅·普罗斯霍尔特 (Maja Proescholdt) 表示，她的离婚程序在没有律师的情况下完成，时间足够长，当文书工作完成时，她的大部分悲伤已经平复，她已经准备好参加派对了。</p><p>她的姐姐提供了一顶王冠和一条“最终离婚”的腰带。乐队出去跳舞，俱乐部的 DJ 喊道：“让我们为 Maja 的离婚派对举办吧！”</p><p> “那对我来说是人生的巅峰时刻，”她说。</p><p>写信给 Lane Florsheim： <a href="mailto:lane.florsheim@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">lane.florsheim@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/7014063b-a894-4b50-b6a3-a3b3e88591aa.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/divorce-parties-registries-marriage-1ed745b9</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/divorce-parties-registries-marriage-1ed745b9<author><![CDATA[Lane Florsheim]]></author><category>阿赫德</category><category>世界时尚</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>结婚/离婚</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>婚姻</category><category>离婚</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Europeans Are Becoming Poorer. ‘Yes, We’re All Worse Off.’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>重视空闲时间的人口老龄化为经济停滞奠定了基础。然后是 Covid-19 和俄罗斯在乌克兰的战争。 <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817790/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="巴黎的一家餐厅。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>巴黎的一家餐厅。西里尔·马西尔哈西/彭博新闻<span>西里尔·马西尔哈西/彭博新闻</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001056065"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001056065"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/tom-fairless" itemprop="url" rel="author">汤姆·费尔莱斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 17 日上午 12:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/europeans-poorer-inflation-economy-255eb629"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>欧洲人正面临着几十年来从未经历过的新经济现实。他们变得越来越穷。</p><p>随着欧洲人的购买力逐渐消失，长期以来因其<em>生活艺术而</em>被外人羡慕的大陆上的生活正在迅速失去光彩。</p><p>法国人正在少吃鹅肝，少喝红酒。西班牙人对橄榄油很吝啬。芬兰人被敦促在大风天使用桑拿浴室，因为那时能源价格较低。在整个德国，肉类和牛奶的消费量已降至三十年来的最低水平，一度繁荣的有机食品市场也陷入了低迷。意大利经济发展部长阿道夫·乌尔索（Adolfo Urso）于五月召开了一次危机会议，讨论该国最受欢迎的主食意大利面的价格，此前意大利面的价格上涨了全国通胀率的两倍多。</p><p>随着消费支出直线下降，欧洲在年初陷入衰退，强化了本世纪初开始出现的经济、政治和军事相对衰退的感觉。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="960" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818002?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>欧洲当前的困境由来已久。人口老龄化导致人们对空闲时间和工作保障的重视超过了收入，导致经济和生产力增长多年来一直乏善可陈。然后是Covid-19大流行和俄罗斯在乌克兰的旷日持久的战争的一对二重击。这场危机颠覆了全球供应链，导致能源和食品价格飙升，加剧了数十年来持续恶化的疾病。</p><p>政府的反应只会让问题更加复杂化。为了保住就业机会，他们主要向雇主提供补贴，导致消费者在价格冲击来临时没有现金缓冲。相比之下，美国人受益于廉价的能源和主要针对公民以保持消费的政府援助。</p><p>过去，非洲大陆强大的出口工业可能会起到拯救作用。但作为欧洲的重要市场，中国的缓慢复苏正在削弱这一增长支柱。高能源成本和自 20 世纪 70 年代以来从未见过的严重通货膨胀正在削弱制造商在国际市场上的价格优势，并破坏非洲大陆曾经和谐的劳资关系。随着全球贸易降温，欧洲对出口的严重依赖（出口占欧元区 GDP 的 50% 左右，而美国仅占 10%）正在成为一个弱点。</p><p>根据经济合作与发展组织（总部位于巴黎、主要由富裕国家组成的俱乐部）的数据，自 2019 年底以来，经过通货膨胀调整后，欧元区 20 国的私人消费下降了约 1%。在美国，劳动力市场强劲且收入不断增加，家庭收入增长了近9%。欧盟目前约占全球消费支出的 18%，而美国这一比例为 28%。十五年前，欧盟和美国各占总数的约四分之一。</p><p>根据通货膨胀和购买力进行调整后，德国的工资自 2019 年以来下降了约 3%，意大利和西班牙下降了 3.5%，希腊下降了 6%。根据经合组织的数据，同期美国的实际工资增长了约 6%。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817793?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一名老妇人离开柏林教堂的食品分发中心。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：马库斯·施赖伯/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>这种痛苦波及到了中产阶级。最近的一个晚上，在欧洲最富有的城市之一布鲁塞尔，教师和护士排队从卡车后面领取半价杂货。供应商欢乐时光市场从超市收集接近保质期的食物，并通过应用程序进行广告。顾客可以在下午早些时候下订单，并在晚上领取打折的杂货。</p><p> “有些顾客告诉我，因为你，我每周可以吃两到三次肉，”正在分发一箱箱杂货的皮埃尔·范赫德说。</p><p> 33 岁的护士卡里姆·布阿扎 (Karim Bouazza) 正在为妻子和两个孩子储备半价肉和鱼，他抱怨说，通货膨胀意味着“你几乎需要做第二份工作来支付一切费用”。</p><p>类似的服务在该地区如雨后春笋般涌现，将自己宣传为减少食物浪费和省钱的一种方式。 TooGoodToGo 是一家于 2015 年在丹麦成立的公司，销售零售商和餐馆的剩余食物，在欧洲拥有 7600 万注册用户，大约是 2020 年底人数的三倍。在德国，2017 年创建的初创公司 Sirplus 提供“在其在线商店中拯救“食品，包括过期的产品。 Motatos 也是如此，它于 2014 年在瑞典创立，目前已进军芬兰、德国、丹麦和英国</p><p>高端杂货的支出大幅下降。 2022年，德国人均肉类消费量为52公斤，比上一年减少约8%，是自1989年开始计算以来的最低水平。虽然其中部分反映了社会对健康饮食和动物福利的担忧，但专家表示，这一趋势正在加速近几个月来肉类价格上涨了30%。据联邦农业信息中心称，德国人也正在将牛肉和小牛肉等肉类换成家禽等较便宜的肉类。</p><p>法兰克福附近的有机食品供应商托马斯·沃尔夫 (Thomas Wolff) 表示，由于通货膨胀飙升，去年他的销售额下降了 30%。沃尔夫表示，他在疫情爆发初期雇佣了 33 名员工来应对对昂贵生态食品的强劲需求，但后来他将他们全部解雇。</p><p> 26 岁的汉堡顾问兼作家罗尼娅·埃贝林 (Ronja Ebeling) 表示，她将大约四分之一的收入储蓄起来，部分原因是她担心没有足够的钱养老。她在衣服或化妆品上花的钱很少，并与伴侣的父亲共用一辆车。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817996?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Weak spending and poor demographic prospects are making Europe less attractive for businesses ranging from consumer-goods giant <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/PG" class="company-name">Procter &amp; Gamble</a> to luxury empire <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/LVMUY" class="">LVMH</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> which are making an ever-larger share of their sales in North America.</p><p> “The US consumer is more resilient than in Europe,” <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UL" class="">Unilever</a> <span class="company-name-type">&#39;s</span></p> chief financial officer, Graeme Pitkethly, said in April.<p></p><p> The eurozone economy grew about 6% over the past 15 years, measured in dollars, compared with 82% for the US, according to International Monetary Fund data. That has left the average EU country poorer per head than every US state except Idaho and Mississippi, according to a report this month by the European Centre for International Political Economy, a Brussels-based independent think tank. If the current trend continues, by 2035 the gap between economic output per capita in the US and EU will be as large as that between Japan and Ecuador today, the report said.</p><p> On the Mediterranean island of Mallorca, businesses are lobbying for more flights to the US to increase the number of free-spending American tourists, said Maria Frontera, president of the Mallorca Chamber of Commerce&#39;s tourism commission. Americans spend about €260 ($292) per day on average on hotels compared with less than €180 ($202) for Europeans.</p><p> “This year we have seen a big change in the behavior of Europeans because of the economic situation we are dealing with,” said Frontera, who recently traveled to Miami to learn how to better cater to American customers. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="789" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817781?width=1260&amp;height=789" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> People enjoy the warm temperatures in a beach bar in the seaside resort of S&#39;Arenal on Mallorca.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Clara Margais/DPA/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Weak growth and rising interest rates are straining Europe&#39;s generous welfare states, which provide popular healthcare services and pensions. European governments find the old recipes for fixing the problem are either becoming unaffordable or have stopped working. Three-quarters of a trillion euros in subsidies, tax breaks and other forms of relief have gone to consumers and businesses to offset higher energy costs—something economists say is now itself fueling inflation, defeating the subsidies&#39; purpose.</p><p> Public-spending cuts after the global financial crisis starved Europe&#39;s state-funded healthcare systems, especially the UK&#39;s National Health Service.</p><p> Vivek Trivedi, a 31-year-old anesthesiologist living in Manchester, England, earns about £51,000 ($67,000) per year for a 48-hour workweek. Inflation, which has been about 10% or higher in the UK for nearly a year, is devouring his monthly budget, he says. Trivedi said he shops for groceries in discount retailers and spends less on meals out. Some colleagues turned off their heating entirely over recent months, worried they wouldn&#39;t be able to afford sharply higher costs, he said.</p><p> Noa Cohen, a 28-year old public-affairs specialist in London, says she could quadruple her salary in the same job by leveraging her US passport to move across the Atlantic. Cohen recently got a 10% pay raise after switching jobs, but the increase was completely swallowed by inflation. She says friends are freezing their eggs because they can&#39;t afford children anytime soon, in the hope that they have enough money in future.</p><p> “It feels like a perma-freeze in living standards,” she said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818000?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Huw Pill, the Bank of England&#39;s chief economist, warned UK citizens in April that they need to accept that they are poorer and stop pushing for higher wages. “Yes, we&#39;re all worse off,” he said, saying that seeking to offset rising prices with higher wages would only fuel more inflation.</p><p> With European governments needing to increase defense spending and given rising borrowing costs, economists expect taxes to increase, adding pressure on consumers. Taxes in Europe are already high relative to those in other wealthy countries, equivalent to around 40-45% of GDP compared with 27% in the US American workers take home almost three-quarters of their paychecks, including income taxes and Social Security taxes, while French and German workers keep just half.</p><p> The pauperization of Europe has bolstered the ranks of labor unions, which are picking up tens of thousands of members across the continent, reversing a decadeslong decline. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817780?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Bank of England has been raising interest rates to combat inflation.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jason Alden/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Higher unionization may not translate into fuller pockets for members. That&#39;s because many are pushing workers&#39; preference for more free time over higher pay, even in a world of spiraling skills shortages.</p><p> IG Metall, Germany&#39;s biggest trade union, is calling for a four-day work week at current salary levels rather than a pay raise for the country&#39;s metalworkers ahead of collective bargaining negotiations this November. Officials say the shorter week would improve workers&#39; health and quality of life while at the same time making the industry more attractive to younger workers.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What is your outlook for the economic health of Europe?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Almost half of employees in Germany&#39;s health industry choose to work around 30 hours per week rather than full time, reflecting tough working conditions, said Frank Werneke, chairman of the country&#39;s United Services Trade Union, which has added about 110,000 new members in recent months, the biggest increase in 22 years.</p><p> Kristian Kallio, a games developer in northern Finland, recently decided to reduce his working week by one-fifth to 30 hours in exchange for a 10% pay cut. He now makes about €2,500 per month. “Who wouldn&#39;t want to work shorter hours?” Kallio said. About one-third of his colleagues took the same deal, although leaders work full-time, said Kallio&#39;s boss, Jaakko Kylmäoja.</p><p> Kallio now works from 10 am to 4.30 pm He uses his extra free time for hobbies, to make good food and take long bike rides. “I don&#39;t see a reality where I would go back to normal working hours,” he said.</p><p> Igor Chaykovskiy, a 34-year-old IT worker in Paris, joined a trade union earlier this year to press for better pay and conditions. He recently received a 3.5% pay increase, about half the level of inflation. He thinks the union will give workers greater leverage to press managers. Still, it isn&#39;t just about pay. “Maybe they say you don&#39;t have an increase in salary, you have free sports lessons or music lessons,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="837" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817792?width=1260&amp;height=837" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Mathias Senn, right, a butcher in Germany&#39;s wealthy Black Forest region, couldn&#39;t find local applicants to replace four workers who are preparing to retire, so he hired an apprentice from India, Rajakumar Bheemappa Lamani.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Dominic Nahr for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> At the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/STLA" class="company-name">Stellantis</a> auto factory in Melfi, southern Italy, employees have worked shorter hours for years recently due to the difficulty of procuring raw materials and high energy costs, said Marco Lomio, a trade unionist with the Italian Union of Metalworkers. Hours worked have recently been reduced by around 30% and wages decreased proportionally.</p><p> “Between high inflation and rising energy costs for workers,” said Lomio, “it is difficult to bear all family expenses.”</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/europeans-poorer-inflation-economy-255eb629</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/europeans-poorer-inflation-economy-255eb629<author><![CDATA[Tom Fairless]]></author><category> leder</category><category>华尔街日报</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>Respiratory Tract Diseases</category><category>健康</category><category>Medical Conditions</category><category> Outbreaks/Epidemics</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>Novel Coronaviruses</category><category> Infectious Diseases</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>respiratory tract diseases</category><category>健康</category><category>medical conditions</category><category> outbreaks</category><category> epidemics</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>novel coronaviruses</category><category> infectious diseases</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Germany in the World’ Review: Reichs, From First to Third]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The young nation-state of Germany turned to fascism and genocide in the 1930s. Yet before 1914 it was as liberal as France or Britain. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12108107398966324280204590080563906716420"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818059?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Brandenburg Gate in Berlin at the end of the 19th century.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Alamy Stock Photo </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12108107398966324280204590080563906716420"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Josef Joffe</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 16, 2023 4:52 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/germany-in-the-world-review-reichs-from-first-to-third-da62f1c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Five hundred years ago, the land we now call Germany existed as the “Holy Roman Empire of the German Nation.” It wasn&#39;t a real empire and certainly wasn&#39;t holy or Roman or even particularly German. It was rather a hodgepodge of fiefdoms, creeds and nationalities. Napoleon put an end to this “empire” in 1806.</p><p> Modern Germany, a babe among the classic nation-states, was born in 1871, when Prussia pounded together 25 little Germanys. Unification triggered growth, then ambition, then two horrifying world wars. Amputation cut the behemoth down to size. Reunified today, Germany is Europe&#39;s largest economy and an admired citizen of the world.</p><p> Yet there are continuities, which is the main theme of David Blackbourn&#39;s “Germany in the World: A Global History, 1500-2000.” These continuities, though, aren&#39;t of the facile character-as-destiny sort—from Luther to Hitler, as a 1941 tome had it. Mr. Blackbourn bids us to look through a “wider lens,” which reveals that Germany was not Europe&#39;s odd-man-out.</p><p> Take German nationalism. He reminds us that the “1860s were a pivotal decade” in the annals of nationalism. Invented by Revolutionary France, the ideology gripped all new nation-states: Germany, Italy and Japan. America, too, went on a nationalist binge in the 1890s. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/7b3bf44f-b8db-410c-9d26-8805a032d050.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> The Kaiser&#39;s Germany was not on a <em>Sonderweg</em> , a separate poisoned path. Nor was the Reich before 1914 less liberal than France or Britain by the standards of the time. Germany was beholden to the rule of law and boasted a strong parliament and a vigorous press. Why did its regime turn to genocide? In spite of the growing literature on the Holocaust, the cosmic riddle remains unsolved.</p><p> Mr. Blackbourn counsels that “we should challenge the persistent idea that landlocked Germany was wrapped up in its own affairs”—an unto-itself—“while others transformed relations between Europe and the non-European world.” In fact, he contends, the “Holy Roman Empire was a world in motion.” Over the next 150 pages, he recounts how Germany&#39;s sailors manned the ships of the seafaring nations, its soldiers served in the British and Dutch empires, and its restless inhabitants struck out from Eastern Europe to the Western Hemisphere.</p><p> Even so, the global wanderlust of German sailors, savants and settlers doesn&#39;t quite compare to what the real globalizers did, conquering and peopling the four corners of the earth. Diaspora isn&#39;t empire, never mind how many millions of Germans settled in the United States; and anyway the few possessions Germany grabbed were lost in the 1919 Versailles settlement. The defeated Germans should thank the victors who spared them countless wars against the locals, which drained the blood and wealth of the colonial powers after World War II.</p><p> The German (or German-speaking) “empire” was a lot cheaper. It was a cultural dominion. We can&#39;t think about modernity without Goethe and Schiller, Bach and Beethoven, Marx and Hegel, Kant and Wittgenstein, Rilke and Mann, Freud and Jung, Einstein, Planck and Heisenberg. Germans like GW Pabst and Fritz Lang wrote the first chapters of the cinematic canon. Carl Laemmle invented Hollywood.</p><p> Mr. Blackbourn reminds us that American higher education was “remade” in the image of the “German model.” Harvard, Stanford and Johns Hopkins (“Göttingen in Baltimore”) adopted the German concept of the research university. Later they profited from a tragic windfall gain, when thousands of German academics found refuge in the US—Hitler&#39;s “gift.”</p><p> Curiously missing from a section of the book titled “The Triumph of German Culture,” spanning the 60 years between Bismarck and Hitler, is the momentous Jewish role. Something like 39 Jewish Nobel laureates hailed from Germany and Austria during this period, and more from the rest of <em>Mitteleuropa</em> . And then there were the writers of fiction, like Franz Kafka, and composers, like Arnold Schoenberg, who broke the mold.</p><p> Mr. Blackbourn&#39;s commendable passion for evenhandedness sometimes gets the better of him. Thus he depicts the boundless slaughter after the Final Solution was formulated in 1942 as, though “German-directed,” a “pan-European operation” by peoples under the German knout, especially in Eastern Europe. This complicity doesn&#39;t obliterate the difference between rider and horse. Nazi Germany designed the project and built the death factories. Some Poles, Ukrainians et al. were willing collaborators. But they were not masters.</p><p> We get a similar whiff of “yes, but” in Mr. Blackbourn&#39;s account of the two world wars. Yes, unrestricted U-boat warfare brought the US into the first, but German civilians suffered under the blockade. And, yes, in the second, German war-making was indiscriminately cruel, but area bombing inflicted terrible misery on German innocents.</p><p> How, other than loss and devastation, did Germany go so fast from fascist dictatorship to peaceable republic? The US solved postwar Germany&#39;s security dilemma by extending its nuclear umbrella. Safety breeds good things: prosperity, democracy and self-containment. The rest of Europe no longer fears the nation that is again No. 1.</p><p> So is the “German Problem” a thing of the past? Not quite. Twelve years ago, as Mr. Blackbourn points out, Poland&#39;s foreign minister remarked that he feared German power less than German inactivity. Sometimes lessons are too well learned. Passivity no longer works as a grand strategy, as Russia made clear when it invaded Ukraine last year and forced Germany to lend its might to the victim.</p><p> Too much of a good thing might also hold for “Germany in the World,” which runs close to 800 pages. The research is magnificent, with 80 pages of endnotes. But the central idea—Germany as a Western nation like the others—is often submerged beneath a torrent of names, details and digressions. That said, the book is superbly written, and even Germany buffs will find a surfeit of riches.</p><p> <em>Mr. Joffe teaches at the Johns Hopkins School of Advanced International Studies.</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 20:52:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/germany-in-the-world-review-reichs-from-first-to-third-da62f1c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/germany-in-the-world-review-reichs-from-first-to-third-da62f1c<category> Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>Arts/Entertainment</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>War Crimes</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>Reviews</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>books</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>arts</category><category>娱乐</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>war crimes</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>reviews</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The New Workday Dead Zone When Nothing Gets Done]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Late afternoon, when many colleagues vanish, is why so many managers hate hybrid work <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816492/?width=2000&amp;size=1.5" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Photo Illustration by Blake Cale for The Wall Street Journal, iStock (2) <span>Photo Illustration by Blake Cale for The Wall Street Journal, iStock (2)</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001051789"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001051789"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/callum-borchers"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-498821" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/callum-borchers" itemprop="url" rel="author">Callum Borchers</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 16, 2023 9:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/work-office-coworkers-schedule-meetings-2af3f9b0"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> The 4 pm meeting is canceled because half the team can&#39;t make it. You send an email with what would have been the main discussion points, and the replies roll in through the evening and into the next morning. A consensus that could have been reached before dinner now forms the following day.</p><p> The hours that bookend the traditional close of business have become a dead zone at many companies, but employees aren&#39;t just blowing off work to relax for the rest of the day. Workers say the 4-6 pm flex time they use to take a turn in the kids&#39; carpool, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-working-out-during-the-workday-is-the-ultimate-power-move-11672863482?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">hit the gym</a> or beat traffic often requires a third shift at night to finish the day&#39;s tasks. They resent it when leaders assume they aren&#39;t putting in eight or more hours of work, and they&#39;re loath to relinquish the freedom to set their own schedules.</p><p> Despite the return of teeth-grinding commutes and overpriced lunches, lots of workers are sticking with the Covid-era habit of clocking out early and making it up later. By 4 pm on weekdays, golf courses are packed, according to a Stanford University <a href="https://nbloom.people.stanford.edu/sites/g/files/sbiybj24291/files/media/file/golfingfromhome.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">study</a> , as are many New York City restaurants.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">Microsoft</a> researchers have documented what they call a “<a href="https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/worklab/triple-peak-day" target="_blank" class="icon none">triple peak</a> ” phenomenon in which workers&#39; keyboard activity spikes in the morning and afternoon, then a third time around 10 pm The tech giant predicts this pattern is here to stay.</p><p> In a recent, one-month sample of Microsoft Teams software usage, the share of virtual and in-person meetings scheduled between 4 pm and 6 pm was down 7% from a year earlier, despite widespread office returns.</p><p> Bosses can drag employees back to their desks, but good luck keeping them there until the end of a 9-to-5 workday or beyond. The 4-6 pm dead zone is one reason so many executives are cranky about hybrid work. They say it&#39;s the hardest time to reach people, and things would be easier if everybody were present and accounted for in person, even though many workers seem to be leaving offices earlier, too.</p><p> <strong>The Price of Flexibility</strong></p><p> Fungible hours are great for those doing the funging. For managers and co-workers, one person&#39;s hiatus can be another&#39;s headache.</p><p> “A lot of companies have taken a loose approach under the belief that we&#39;re all adults, so everyone will be self-disciplined and stay motivated at whatever time they&#39;re working,” says Albert Fong, vice president of product marketing at Kanarys, a maker of diversity-training software. “That&#39;s just not true.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="622" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816891?width=639&amp;height=622" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Albert Fong, VP of product marketing at Kanarys, says flexibility can be a trap that fuels our always-on work culture.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Albert Fong</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Flexibility can be a trap that fuels our always-on work culture, Fong adds. Instead of powering through a late-afternoon gathering and being done for the day, he often finds himself refreshing his mobile inbox all evening or opening his laptop on Sunday to catch up on messages from colleagues who work whenever.</p><p> Colette Stallbaumer, general manager of Microsoft&#39;s Future of Work initiative, sums it up: “How do we make it so that my flexibility isn&#39;t your challenge?”</p><p> Ana Paula Calvo, an associate partner at McKinsey &amp; Co., says she considers how shifting her hours can affect others. She sometimes works at night or on weekends to make up for bolting to daycare many weekdays at 5:30 pm At the start of any new project, she does a norm-setting session to let her team know there&#39;s no pressure for them to work off hours.</p><p> “People know that if I get back to them at 11 at night, that doesn&#39;t mean I&#39;m expecting them to reply right away,” she says.</p><p> <strong>It Can Wait—Or Maybe It Can&#39;t</strong></p><p> Accommodating employees&#39; personal appointments—happy-hour yoga, a teen&#39;s tuba lesson—can be necessary to recruit and retain top talent, several business leaders tell me. They add it sure makes getting a quorum at meetings tough, though. Others, especially child-free workers, complain that their workdays have become longer and less predictable since it became widely acceptable to take breaks during normal business hours.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What are you and your colleagues doing from 4-6 pm?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Maria Banach, a pharmaceutical operations director in Oregon, says she sometimes wants to call a huddle to handle a problem, only to learn that someone on the team has gone offline for a couple of hours. That might not seem very long, but her co-workers are spread across several time zones and their overlapping business hours are limited. Issues can linger overnight when one or two people step away early, Banach says, and every day is precious. The drugs her company manufactures expire 17 days after production.</p><p> “Scheduling meetings has become difficult, and I&#39;ve learned: Do it in the morning and never on Friday,” she says.</p><p> Some executives have accepted, even embraced, the reality that little gets done from 4-6 pm Anthony Stephan,</p> chief learning officer of Deloitte US, says recorded tutorials are now a centerpiece of the firm&#39;s professional-development program. Getting employees together for an end-of-the-day training session is seldom an option any more, he says. They hone new skills when they feel like it.<p></p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="852" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815827?width=639&amp;height=852" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Mercedes Aycinena, CEO of Komet USA, usually leaves the office at 5 pm to spend time with her children and then resumes work later if needed.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Mercedes Aycinena</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Stephan, a father of five, holds himself to a hard stop at 5 pm He initially worried that others would keep hustling after he called it a day, but he now realizes others are winding down early or right on time. For emergencies, he tells his team to put #criticalnow in an email subject line. Most things can wait until after his 5:15 am workout the next morning, he figures.</p><p> At Komet USA, a South Carolina-based maker of dental equipment, meetings after 4 pm or on Friday afternoon are against company policy, except in special circumstances. Chief Executive Mercedes Aycinena, promoted to the top job last year, introduced those calendar blocks last fall after polling the staff.</p><p> Aycinena, who has about 100 employees, usually leaves the office at 5 pm to spend time with her three children and then resumes work later as needed. She lets subordinates shift their hours, too, and credits flexibility with helping reduce turnover from 50% to 15% over the past year.</p><p> “I hate meetings after 4,” she says. “My brain is done.”</p><p> Write to Callum Borchers at <a href="mailto:callum.borchers@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">callum.borchers@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/12865c40-068f-4100-aa18-f73fd5f66fae.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 13:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/work-office-coworkers-schedule-meetings-2af3f9b0</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/work-office-coworkers-schedule-meetings-2af3f9b0<author><![CDATA[Callum Borchers]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>Labor/Personnel</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Work-Life Balance</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>General Labor Issues</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>Telecommuting</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> labor</category><category> personnel</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>work-life balance</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>general labor issues</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>telecommuting</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Arts Calendar for the Week of July 16]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> &#39;Barbie&#39; and &#39;Oppenheimer&#39; finally hit theaters, a harrowing documentary looks at the extreme sport of freediving, Britpop icon Blur is back and more. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJO-0000022672"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817403?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ryan Gosling and Margot Robbie</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Warner Bros.</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJO-0000022672"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> WSJ Arts in Review Staff</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 16, 2023 5:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/arts-calendar-happenings-for-the-week-of-july-16-airdigital-8919e68"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><h3> Film</h3><p> <strong>“Barbie”</strong> <em>(July 21)</em> : The Barbie girl finally invites viewers into her Barbie world in one of the summer&#39;s most anticipated films. Margot Robbie plays the iconic <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MAT" class="company-name">Mattel</a> creation with Ryan Gosling as her Ken in a film with more stars than rooms in a Malibu Dreamhouse. America Ferrera, Rhea Perlman, Kate McKinnon, Issa Rae, Dua Lipa, Simu Liu, John Cena, Helen Mirren, Michael Cera and more play dress up in the movie directed by Greta Gerwig that she wrote with Noah Baumbach.</p><p> <strong>“Oppenheimer”</strong> <em>(July 21)</em> : Another seismic cinema event of the summer, Christopher Nolan&#39;s long-awaited biopic about the theoretical physicist who helped develop the atomic bomb stars Cillian Murphy in the title role alongside other Hollywood familiars like Emily Blunt, Matt Damon, Robert Downey Jr., Florence Pugh, Rami Malek and Kenneth Branagh.</p><p> <strong>“Cobweb”</strong> <em>(July 21)</em> : If the Barbenheimer hype doesn&#39;t have you excited, horror fans have other options this week, including this story of an eight-year-old who tries to uncover a nefarious secret about his home that his parents have been hiding from him. Samuel Bodin directs from a script by Chris Thomas Devlin (2022&#39;s “Texas Chainsaw Massacre”), Seth Rogen and Evan Goldberg are among its producers.</p><p> <strong>“The Beanie Bubble”</strong> <em>(July 21)</em> : Toys are having a big week at the multiplex; this product-friendly offering looks at the viral success of Beanie Babies. Zach Galifianakis stars as Ty Warner, founder of the company that made the cuddly critters, alongside Elizabeth Banks, Sarah Snook and Geraldine Viswanathan. Kristin Gore and Damian Kulash&#39;s dramedy gets a limited theatrical run before heading to Apple TV+.</p><p> <strong>“Fear the Night”</strong> <em>(July 21)</em> : Filmmaker, playwright and actor Neil LaBute is in the director&#39;s chair for this action thriller about an Iraq War vet (played by Maggie Q) who puts her training to good use against a group of home invaders who disrupt her sister&#39;s bachelorette party.</p><h3> TV</h3><p> <strong>“Southern Storytellers”</strong> <em>(PBS, July 18)</em> : Craig Renaud&#39;s three-episode miniseries is a love letter to the American South and the creativity that thrives there. Profiling musicians, writers, filmmakers and more, Mr. Renaud explores not just the creative process but the unique history and environment that has led these artists down their current paths. Interview subjects include novelist Angie Thomas, musicians Lyle Lovett, Jason Isbell and Amanda Shires, actor Billy Bob Thornton and culinary historian Michael Twitty.</p><p> <strong>“Goliath”</strong> <em>(Showtime, July 16)</em> : Rob Ford and Christopher Dillon direct a three-part documentary series on Showtime examining the legacy and character of basketball legend Wilt Chamberlain. Our TV critic <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/goliath-review-how-wilt-chamberlain-changed-the-game-518350d4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">noted</a> that “the flesh-and-blood humans who appear throughout &#39;Goliath&#39; are refreshingly candid, informative and likable.”</p><p> <strong>“Justified: City Primeval”</strong> <em>(FX, July 18)</em> : The follow-up to the Emmy-winning crime drama is here, with Timothy Olyphant back as US Marshal Raylan Givens. Like the previous show, this miniseries draws from the work of Elmore Leonard—this time his novel “City Primeval: High Noon in Detroit”—to rustle up its neo-Western story.</p><p> <strong>“The Deepest Breath”</strong> <em>(Netflix, July 19)</em> : Those with fears of the ocean should avoid Laura McGann&#39;s documentary about freediving, a sport where people try to dive as deep as they can on a single breath of air without any safety equipment. She follows Italian champion Alessia Zecchini as she tries to set a record and navigate an underwater tunnel deep below the Red Sea.</p><p> <strong>“Praise Petey”</strong> <em>(Freeform, July 21)</em> : After her father dies, a New York socialite becomes a different kind of influencer when she takes over his small-town cult in this animated series with Annie Murphy, John Cho, Stephen Root, Christine Baranski and Kiersey Clemons providing the voice talent.</p><p> <strong>“Stephen Curry: Underrated”</strong> <em>(Apple TV+, July 21)</em> : While he might not be on the level of Jordan or Kareem, Steph is still in the GOAT conversation and has undeniably changed the game of basketball forever with his mind-blowing play from behind the arc. Peter Nicks&#39;s new documentary looks at how the superstar Warrior got to where he is today, from humble high-school beginnings, to a college career where his size was an issue, to becoming an NBA champion.</p><p> <strong>“They Cloned Tyrone”</strong> <em>(Netflix, July 21)</em> : A government genetic conspiracy goes awry in Juel Taylor&#39;s sci-fi comedy that stars John Boyega, Teyonah Parris, Jamie Foxx, David Alan Grier and Kiefer Sutherland. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817404?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Alessia Zecchini in &#39;The Deepest Breath&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Netflix</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>剧院</h3><p><strong>“Here Lies Love”</strong> <em>(Broadway Theatre, New York, opens July 20)</em> : Talking Heads frontman David Byrne might be an odd if not totally surprising name to associate with Broadway, especially after his hit show “American Utopia.” But Fatboy Slim? The two teamed with choreographer Annie-B Parson and director Alex Timbers on a musical whose topic itself is unconventional: the rise and fall of Filipino First Lady</p> Imelda Marcos.<p></p><h3> Music</h3><p> <strong>Blur, “The Ballad of Darren”</strong> <em>(July 21)</em> : English rockers Blur, whose rivalry with Oasis made Britpop a worldwide phenomenon, returns with their first album in nearly a decade. Working with producer James Ford, the band offers a record that embraces their classic sound and the concerns of their generation while also aiming to be of-the-moment.</p><p> <strong>Jaboukie, “All Who Can&#39;t Hear Must Feel”</strong> <em>(July 21)</em> : Actor, writer and comedian Jaboukie Young-White is adding another line to his résumé: recording artist. His first album tackles the struggles of growing up the child of immigrants and celebrates his sexuality.</p><p> <strong>Nils Lofgren, “Mountains”</strong> <em>(July 21)</em> : Part of Bruce Springsteen&#39;s E Street Band and</p> Neil Young&#39;s Crazy Horse, the multi-instrumentalist&#39;s new solo LP includes features from Mr. Young, David Crosby (who died before the album was released) and Ringo Starr.<p></p><h3> Dance</h3><p> <strong>“One Dance”</strong> <em>(David H. Koch Theater, New York, July 20-22)</em> : The Seoul Metropolitan Dance Theatre offers a contemporary take on traditional Korean dance and music in this limited engagement choreographed by Hyejin Jung with Sung Hoon Kim and Jae Duk Kim.</p><h3>歌剧</h3><p><strong>“Henri VIII”</strong> <em>(Fisher Center, Annandale-on-Hudson, July 21-30)</em> : Part of the Bard SummerScape festival, Camille Saint-Saëns&#39;s opera about the king&#39;s quest to divorce Catherine of Aragon to wed Anne Boleyn gets a new staging from Jean-Romain Vesperini. Alfred Walker sings the title role with Lindsay Ammann and Amanda Woodbury playing his ill-fated wives.</p><h3>艺术</h3><p><strong>“Tree &amp; Serpent: Early Buddhist Art in India, 200 BCE–400 CE”</strong> <em>(The Met Fifth Avenue, New York, July 21-Nov. 13)</em> : An exhibition tells the story of the origins of Buddhist art and its ineluctable influence on the region and its history. More than 140 objects trace the narrative from its pre-religious sculptural beginnings through international exchanges of secular and spiritual ideas and artifacts.</p><p> <strong>“Edward Hopper &amp; Cape Ann: Illuminating an American Landscape”</strong> <em>(Cape Ann Museum, Gloucester, Mass., July 22-Oct. 16)</em> : Timed to open on the great American painter&#39;s birthday, this show of more than 60 works examines a pivotal point in his career when he visited Cape Ann and was taken by the beauty of its natural and man-made vistas. Also included are works by Josephine N. Hopper, his muse and wife, but also an accomplished painter.</p><p> <strong>Upstate Art Weekend</strong> <em>(Various locations, New York, July 21-24)</em> : Since launching in 2020, this annual collaboration between art spaces throughout the Hudson Valley and the Catskills has expanded to include over 130 participants. These include institutions like Magazzino Italian Art, galleries like Susan Eley Fine Art, performance venues like the Hudson Valley Shakespeare Festival, historical locales like the Thomas Cole National Historic Site and more.</p><h3>其他</h3><p><strong>“Pikmin 4”</strong> <em>(Nintendo Switch, July 21)</em> : The acclaimed puzzle series, in which players rally groups of beleafed creatures called Pikmin to overcome challenges, is back with its first installment since 2013.</p><h3> Last Call</h3><p> <strong>“Peter Pan Goes Wrong”</strong> <em>(Barrymore Theatre, New York, closes July 23)</em> : From the creators of the hit comedy “The Play That Goes Wrong,” this production sees another group of devoted if less-than-capable theater folk trying to stage a show, this time the 1904 JM Barrie classic “Peter and Wendy.”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —For additional Arts Calendar listings visit wsj.com. Write to brian.kelly@wsj.com and julia.fischer@wsj.com.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 09:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/arts-calendar-happenings-for-the-week-of-july-16-airdigital-8919e68</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/arts-calendar-happenings-for-the-week-of-july-16-airdigital-8919e68<category> arts in review</category><category> Games</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Celebrities</category><category> Dance/Ballet</category><category> Electronic Sports</category><category> Arts/Entertainment</category><category> Feature Films</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>TV/Radio Listings</category><category>电影</category><category>Music</category><category>歌剧</category><category>Sports</category><category>剧院</category><category>Television/Radio</category><category> Calendar of Events</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>IWE过滤器</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>Arts in Review</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> games</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>celebrities</category><category> dance</category><category> ballet</category><category> electronic sports</category><category> arts</category><category>娱乐</category><category>feature films</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>tv</category><category> radio listings</category><category> movies</category><category> music</category><category> opera</category><category> sports</category><category> theater</category><category> television</category><category> radio</category><category> calendar of events</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>伊威过滤器</category><category>常规新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Watercolors Unboxed’ Review: Luminous, Liquid Visions]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The Worcester Art Museum rolls out a selection of its world-class collection of watercolors, rarely seen due to their fragility, by artists such as Winslow Homer, John Singer Sargent, Amedeo Modigliani and Jacob Lawrence. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12405162827514393453404590053711666675490"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="564" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817308?width=860&amp;height=564" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Muddy Alligators&#39; (1917) by John Singer Sargent</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Worcester Art Museum </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12405162827514393453404590053711666675490"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Barrymore Laurence Scherer</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 15, 2023 7:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/watercolors-unboxed-review-worcester-sargent-homer-modigliani-lawrence-7a2421b4"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <em>Worcester, Mass.</em></p><p> Think “art museum,” and big-city institutions like Washington&#39;s National Gallery, the Art Institute of Chicago and New York&#39;s Metropolitan first spring to mind. But the current “Watercolors Unboxed” show at the Worcester Art Museum in central Massachusetts makes you realize that regional museums throughout the US often harbor treasures that rank with those of the majors. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4></h4><p> <em>Watercolors Unboxed</em></p><p> <strong>Worcester Art Museum, through Sept. 10</strong></p></div></div><p> Founded in 1896, the Worcester Art Museum not only boasts admirable collections of European and American painting and sculpture, superb mosaics, some 3,700 Japanese woodblock prints, and the famed John Woodman Higgins Armory Collection—it also houses a celebrated trove of watercolors, which because of their fragility and sensitivity to light are rarely displayed.</p><p> Through Sept. 10, WAM is presenting a choice selection of 40 European and American works created between the 1870s and 1950s representing a variety of artistic approaches to this subtle but challenging medium. Organized by Nancy Kathryn Burns, WAM&#39;s curator of prints, drawings and photographs, the show features rarely exhibited watercolors by such American luminaries as Childe Hassam, Winslow Homer, Rockwell Kent, John La Farge, John Singer Sargent and Andrew Wyeth (his riveting 1957 “The Rope,” a study for “Hay Ledge”). It also includes examples by artists less known for their activity in watercolor and gouache (also called “opaque watercolor”), notably Amedeo Modigliani, Gustave Baumann and Ernst Ludwig Kirchner. These newly unboxed paintings range stylistically from Sargent&#39;s bravura brushwork to the deliberate poster-like rawness of social commentator Jacob Lawrence&#39;s 1943 “They live In firetraps.” Also featured are examples from WAM&#39;s collection of watercolors painted or influenced by members of the San Ildefonso school, a collective of Native American artists working in the Southwest during the first half of the 20th century. Because most of these pieces have so long been safely archived, they are in prime condition, their fragile pigments fresh and unfaded. Moreover, beyond reflecting over 70 years&#39; progression of watercolor styles, they illustrate a variety of techniques employed by the artists to achieve their effects, some not always obvious to viewers. Informative technical discussions are included in the wall cards. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="489" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817310?width=700&amp;height=489" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Yonkers From the Palisades&#39; (1916) by Childe Hassam</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Worcester Art Museum</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> For example, Childe Hassam&#39;s 1916 “Yonkers From the Palisades,” a panoramic view looking across the Hudson River from New Jersey&#39;s craggy shore, achieves textural contrast between the quick, fragmented brush strokes of the cliffs and their autumnal foliage and his flowing, idealized blue water. To paint the river, Hassam applied layers of blue and yellow-green wash, before tamping them down with a bit of sponge or other absorbent material.</p><p> Similarly, Rockwell Kent&#39;s 1926-27 “Boy on Cliff” demonstrates wash manipulated to create a different effect: Here, a lone youth, precariously balancing on a narrow rock outcropping, ponders the sea below. Kent surrounds the boy&#39;s head with a mystic aureole of light against the picture&#39;s glowing polychrome sky. As Ms. Burns observed to me, “he produced that sky by brushing adjacent washes of various hues, and most probably using a similar absorbent material to apply further layers of blue and rose tones.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="484" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817309?width=700&amp;height=484" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Venice&#39; (1911) by Maurice Prendergast</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Worcester Art Museum </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> More Art Reviews</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-curatorial-imagination-of-walter-hopps-review-seeing-like-a-visionary-70cec571?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;The Curatorial Imagination of Walter Hopps&#39; Review: Seeing Like a Visionary</a> <span class="date">July 8, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/frank-stewarts-nexus-an-american-photographers-journey-1960s-to-the-present-review-visual-music-22dda449?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Frank Stewart&#39;s Nexus: An American Photographer&#39;s Journey, 1960s to the Present&#39; Review: Visual Music</a> <span class="date">July 4, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/edvard-munch-trembling-earth-review-man-screams-nature-whispers-68da01ff?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Edvard Munch: Trembling Earth&#39; Review: Man Screams, Nature Whispers</a> <span class="date">July 1, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/young-picasso-in-paris-review-a-giant-comes-of-age-4ea04e4f?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Young Picasso in Paris&#39; Review: A Giant Comes of Age</a> <span class="date">June 24, 2023</span></li></ul></div></div><p> Altogether different in mood, Maurice Prendergast&#39;s effervescent “Venice” (1911) exemplifies his well-known use of staccato dabs of color with which he recorded the view outside his Venetian hospital window while recuperating from emergency surgery during a painting holiday there. Characteristically, he makes the mosaic-like dabs scintillate by leaving surrounding areas of the cream paper visible.</p><p> Not surprisingly, Sargent and Homer are easily the show&#39;s stars. Sargent&#39;s “Muddy Alligators” (1917) is among his most exceptional watercolor essays, painted during a trip to Florida after he had essentially abandoned portraiture for the landscape painting that had long been his great love. Over graphite outlines, he loosely deploys quick patches of watercolor to capture a group of these fearsome reptiles lolling about their swampy habitat. Sargent pools some patches and scrapes away others—notably to form the sharp teeth of the open-mouthed gator in the foreground. Hanging alongside the painting, three of Sargent&#39;s detailed pencil sketches of alligators reveal the intensive preparatory study behind the artist&#39;s apparent spontaneity. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="489" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817307?width=700&amp;height=489" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Rum Cay&#39; (1898-99) by Winslow Homer</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Worcester Art Museum</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Created during Homer&#39;s second visit to the Bahamas, “Rum Cay” (1898-99) shows a muscular Bahamian running past a large sea turtle against a minimal beachscape comprising three spare horizontal bands of color wash. Apart from the oblique reference to Aesop&#39;s tortoise and hare, the runner bespeaks Homer&#39;s consummate skill at capturing the athletic human body in action, from the splendid delineation of the man&#39;s face and sunlit torso to the flexed toes of his left foot. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="901" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817361?width=639&amp;height=901" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Homer&#39;s &#39;Old Friends&#39; (1894)</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Worcester Art Museum</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In contrast, Homer&#39;s “Old Friends” (1894) conveys the deep emotion of a rugged old woodsman contemplating a massive ancient tree. Homer&#39;s expressive rendering of the man&#39;s upturned face underscores the emotional link. The composition illustrates his use of “subtractive” painting: Though Homer evidently depicted the Adirondack woodland surrounding the man and the enormous trunk, he subsequently scraped away the paint at the left of the sheet, fashioning a br ight white cloud out of the white paper&#39;s now roughened surface to emphasize the great tree&#39;s majestic presence. Having first seen this profoundly moving work when it was lent by the WAM, along with Sargent&#39;s “Muddy Alligators” and “Bathers,” to the 2017 show “American Watercolor in the Age of Homer and Sargent” at the Philadelphia Museum of Art, I can declare on seeing it this time that familiarity certainly has not bred contempt.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Mr. Scherer writes about music and the fine arts for the Journal.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 15 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/watercolors-unboxed-review-worcester-sargent-homer-modigliani-lawrence-7a2421b4</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/watercolors-unboxed-review-worcester-sargent-homer-modigliani-lawrence-7a2421b4<category> arts in review</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Arts/Entertainment</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>Reviews</category><category> Arts in Review</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>arts</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>reviews </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Joseph Losey’s ‘The Servant’: That Touch of Crass]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The 1963 film adaptation of Robin Maugham&#39;s novella explores class tensions through the lens of the crumbling relationship between an aristocrat and his cunning valet <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12405162827514393453404590055673424606044"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-814178?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Dirk Bogarde and James Fox</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Studiocanal/Shutterstock </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12405162827514393453404590055673424606044"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">David Mermelstein</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 14, 2023 5:24 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/joseph-loseys-the-servant-that-touch-of-crass-8558fe5b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Had Robin Maugham been less stubborn, we might not have the director Joseph Losey&#39;s serenely chilling 1963 film adaptation of Maugham&#39;s novella “The Servant.” But Maugham, a nephew of the writer W. Somerset Maugham and later a hereditary viscount, was determined to turn “The Servant,” first published in 1948, into a play and unwilling to sell the movie rights if such a deal also included those for the stage.</p><p> At first, it hardly mattered, for “The Servant,” a sly parable of class dislocation and moral rot, was initially considered unfilmable. But by the time Maugham finished his theatrical adaptation in 1958, society had changed enough for a motion picture to be contemplated.</p><p> Initially, the Wisconsin-born, Ivy League-educated Losey, exiled from Hollywood at the height of the McCarthy era for his Communist sympathies, wanted to direct Maugham&#39;s stage adaptation. But that production never materialized. And only later did Losey pursue the project for the screen. First-hand accounts differ as to how exactly Maugham&#39;s novella wound up with the winning combination of Losey as director, the already distinguished playwright Harold Pinter as screenwriter and the actor Dirk Bogarde, a matinee idol in transition, as Barrett, the title character. But such details are unimportant. The finished product was and remains one of the great British films of its decade.</p><p> And now the picture has been released in a way that befits its status, in an immensely satisfying 4K restoration on Blu-ray from the Criterion Collection, following a theatrical rerelease last year. Seasoned cineastes have long awaited this day, for Douglas Slocombe&#39;s striking black-and-white cinematography is among the movie&#39;s many outstanding features. His use of deep focus and the shots where the action is reflected in mirrors only augment the film&#39;s discomfiting vision, further signaling that nothing is quite as it first appears.</p><p> The story is uncomplicated, though no less distressing for its directness. The highborn Tony, played with effective callowness by a young James Fox, hires a manservant, the creepy but highly skilled Barrett, which finds Bogarde in the first of his career-defining roles. As Tony becomes increasingly dependent on Barrett, his connections to the outside world diminish, particularly his relationship with his fiancée, Susan, coolly played by a hard-edged Wendy Craig. A fourth character, Vera—purportedly Barrett&#39;s sister but clearly something else—helps propel Tony&#39;s presumably irreversible descent, with Sarah Miles&#39;s portrayal handily oscillating between innocent and cunning. The novella&#39;s intermittently present narrator is dispensed with entirely on screen. For, as Pinter noted, the viewer assumes that perspective.</p><p> Maugham&#39;s compulsively readable book (fewer than 75 pages) is elliptical, broadly sketched and swift-moving, whereas Losey&#39;s film is lapidary, densely packed and tense. Both plumb depths far beyond their surface details—not just class distinctions, but unblinking explorations of human nature at its least flattering.</p><p> In many ways, Losey&#39;s picture eclipses its inspiration. Maugham describes Barrett repeatedly as reptilian. But by casting the suave Bogarde, the director invests the valet with added powers of manipulation—surpassing corruption and veering toward seduction. Maugham&#39;s book merely hints at a sexual connection between master and servant, but Pinter&#39;s screenplay comes tantalizingly close to depicting it. (What happens after the final credits roll is anyone&#39;s guess.)</p><p> All of this is conveyed expertly by Losey, and made all the more effective by his use of a cramped London townhouse that he and Richard Macdonald, the production designer, furnished with obsessive care. In an especially sly nod, the house&#39;s ancestral paintings actually belonged to Maugham. The intricacy of the mise-en-scène, with its forced intimacy and inspired use of mirrors as metaphor, only heightens the action and the sting of Pinter&#39;s barbed language. In one delicious moment of foreshadowing, Barrett says to Susan: “I&#39;m afraid it&#39;s not very encouraging, Miss . 。 。 the weather forecast.”</p><p> Less often appreciated is the saxophonist and composer John Dankworth&#39;s</p> off-kilter jazz soundtrack, which seamlessly melds free-spiritedness and foreboding. Though rooted firmly in its time, it also transcends its era and lends nascent Swinging London a sinister cast.<p></p><p> At the center of “The Servant” stands an ugly truth: Humans are weak creatures, prone to temptation and even, sometimes, degradation. That, alas, is our lot. Maugham, Pinter and Losey are merely, pitilessly, holding up the looking glass.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Mr. Mermelstein, the Journal&#39;s classical music critic, also writes on film.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 14 Jul 2023 21:24:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/joseph-loseys-the-servant-that-touch-of-crass-8558fe5b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/joseph-loseys-the-servant-that-touch-of-crass-8558fe5b<category> arts in review</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Arts/Entertainment</category><category>电影</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>Arts in Review</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>arts</category><category>娱乐</category><category>movies</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item></channel></rss>